{
  "doc_id": "48517",
  "text": "Rheumatoid arthritis (RA) is a chronic systemic inflammatory disease characterized by articular and extraarticular manifestations involving cardiovascular diseases, which accounts for 30 to 50% of all deaths [CITATION_1] . Recent studies showed that atherosclerosis lesions occur earlier and have a more rapid evolution in RA patients than in the general population [CITATION_2] . Endothelial dysfunction is thought to be a key event in the development of atherosclerosis and has been identified in patients with RA, even in the early diagnosed arthritis [CITATION_3] . It is generally defined as impaired endothelium-dependent vasodilation to specific stimuli and characterized by an imbalance between vasoconstriction and vasodilation factors. Although the improvement of endothelial function is recognized as an important element of the global management of RA patients [CITATION_4] , the precise pathophysiological mechanisms of endothelial dysfunction in RA are still poorly understood.",
